101. 9. religiosi arelegendo. See note 1, a, 3. The verse cited by Gellius IV, 9: relegentem te oportet esse, religiosus ue fuas (for that is the true reading), cannot be held to warrant the derivation given in the text by Cicero, as religans is not a current word, but one manufactured by the poet to support that derivation. Competent scholars have long thought that no grammatical objection lies against the derivation from religare, especially when it is considered that there was an old form legire for ligare. Comp. Ebel in the Zeitsch. t'. vgl. Sprachk. IV, p. 449.
